# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: defense-c4isr
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:defense-c4isr/battle-command] Business processes associated with command and control of military forces are detailed in various publications of the United States Department of Defense.
[src:defense-c4isr/battle-command] Modern **BC** software and hardware exhibit all of the traits and qualities of an SoS.
[src:defense-c4isr/battle-command] A **BC** SoS can be decomposed into systems such as maneuvers, logistics, fires and effects, air support, intelligence, surveillance, reconnaissance (alternatively recognizance) (these three sometimes grouped as ISR, or by adding target acquisition, ISTAR), terrain, and weather.
[src:defense-c4isr/battle-command] Among the many inputs of these systems is a plethora of sensors which undergo sensor fusion and are compiled into a common operational picture/local operational picture that enable commanders to achieve situational awareness (SA)/situational understanding (SU).
[src:defense-c4isr/battle-command] SA/SU is paramount for commanders to command and control modern military forces.
[src:defense-c4isr/battle-command] The Department of the Army organization primarily responsible for the acquisition of the **BC** SoS is the PM BC, a subordinate organization within the PEO C3T.
[src:defense-c4isr/battle-command] One of the problems with **BC** SoS is that a commander has little communication while in the battlefield.
[src:defense-c4isr/battle-command] Command and control planning occurs at a command post (CP) or tactical operations center (TOC).
[src:defense-c4isr/battle-command] Once a battle begins, a commander leaves the CP/TOC and moves forward to stay engaged.
[src:defense-c4isr/battle-command] A commander has limited communication possibilities while in the battlefield, making it difficult to follow and control all events as they happen.
[src:defense-c4isr/battle-command] *Battle command on the move* (BCOTM) is a capability that provides commanders all of the information resident in their CP/TOC and the required communications necessary to command and control on the move, or at a short halt, from any vantage point on the battlefield.
[src:defense-c4isr/command-and-control] Versions of the United States Army *Field Manual 3-0* circulated circa 1999 define C2 in a military organization as the exercise of authority and direction by a properly designated commanding officer over assigned and attached forces in the accomplishment of a mission.
[src:defense-c4isr/command-and-control] A 1988 NATO definition is that command and control is the exercise of authority and direction by a properly designated individual over assigned resources in the accomplishment of a common goal.
[src:defense-c4isr/command-and-control] An Australian Defence Force definition, similar to that of NATO, emphasises that C2 is the system empowering designated personnel to exercise lawful authority and direction over assigned forces for the accomplishment of missions and tasks.
[src:defense-c4isr/command-and-control] The Australian doctrine goes on to state: "The use of agreed terminology and definitions is fundamental to any C2 system and the development of joint doctrine and procedures.
[src:defense-c4isr/command-and-control] The US *Department of Defense Dictionary of Military and Associated Terms* defines command and control as: "The exercise of authority and direction by a properly designated commander over assigned and attached forces in the accomplishment of the mission.
[src:defense-c4isr/command-and-control] Commanding officers are assisted in executing these tasks by specialized staff officers and enlisted personnel.
[src:defense-c4isr/command-and-control] These *military staff* are a group of officers and enlisted personnel that provides a bi-directional flow of information between a commanding officer and subordinate military units.
[src:defense-c4isr/command-and-control] The purpose of a military staff is mainly that of providing accurate, timely information which by category represents information on which command decisions are based.
[src:defense-c4isr/command-and-control] The key application is that of decisions that effectively manage unit resources.
[src:defense-c4isr/command-and-control] While information flow toward the commander is a priority, information that is useful or contingent in nature is communicated to lower staffs and units.
[src:defense-c4isr/command-and-control] This term is also in common use within the computer security industry and in the context of cyberwarfare.
[src:defense-c4isr/command-and-control] Here the term refers to the influence an attacker has over a compromised computer system that they control.
[src:defense-c4isr/command-and-control] For example, a valid usage of the term is to say that attackers use "command and control infrastructure" to issue "command and control instructions" to their victims.
[src:defense-c4isr/command-and-control] Advanced analysis of command and control methodologies can be used to identify attackers, associate attacks, and disrupt ongoing malicious activity.
[src:defense-c4isr/command-and-control] There is a plethora of derivative terms that emphasize various aspects, uses, and sub-domains of C2.
[src:defense-c4isr/command-and-control] These terms are accompanied by numerous associated abbreviations.
[src:defense-c4isr/command-and-control] Command: The exercise of authority based upon certain knowledge to attain an objective.
[src:defense-c4isr/command-and-control] Control: The process of verifying and correcting activity such that the objective or goal of command is accomplished.
[src:defense-c4isr/command-and-control] Communication: Ability to exercise the necessary liaison to exercise effective command between tactical or strategic units to command.
[src:defense-c4isr/command-and-control] Computers: The computer systems and compatibility of computer systems.
[src:defense-c4isr/command-and-control] Intelligence: Includes collection as well as analysis and distribution of information.
[src:defense-c4isr/command-and-control] A **command and control center** is typically a secure room or building in a government, military or prison facility that operates as the agency's dispatch center, surveillance monitoring center, coordination office and alarm monitoring center all in one.
[src:defense-c4isr/command-and-control] Command and control centers are operated by a government or municipal agency.
[src:defense-c4isr/command-and-control] Various branches of the US military such as the US Coast Guard and Navy have command and control centers.
[src:defense-c4isr/command-and-control] They are also common in many large correctional facilities.
[src:defense-c4isr/command-and-control] A command and control center that is used by a military unit in a deployed location is usually called a "command post".
[src:defense-c4isr/command-and-control] Command and control warfare encompasses all the military tactics that use communications technology.
[src:defense-c4isr/command-and-control] An older name for these tactics is "signals warfare", derived from the name given to communications by the military.
[src:defense-c4isr/command-and-control] Newer names include information operations and information warfare.
[src:defense-c4isr/command-and-control] with the physical destruction of enemy communications facilities.
[src:defense-c4isr/command-and-control] The objective is to deny information to the enemy and so disrupt its command and control capabilities.
[src:defense-c4isr/command-and-control] At the same time precautions are taken to protect friendly command and control capabilities against retaliation.
[src:defense-c4isr/command-and-control] In addition to targeting the enemy's command and control, information warfare can be directed to the enemy's politicians and other civilian communications.
[src:defense-c4isr/data-link] A **data link** is a means of connecting one location to another for the purpose of transmitting and receiving digital information (data communication).
[src:defense-c4isr/data-link] It can also refer to a set of electronics assemblies, consisting of a transmitter and a receiver (two pieces of data terminal equipment) and the interconnecting data telecommunication circuit.
[src:defense-c4isr/data-link] These are governed by a link protocol enabling digital data to be transferred from a data source to a data sink.
[src:defense-c4isr/data-link] In civil aviation, a data-link system (known as Controller Pilot Data Link Communications) is used to send information between aircraft and air traffic controllers for example when an aircraft is too far from the ATC to make voice radio communication and radar observations possible.
[src:defense-c4isr/data-link] Such systems are used for aircraft crossing the Atlantic, Pacific and Indian oceans.
[src:defense-c4isr/data-link] One such system, used by Nav Canada and NATS over the North Atlantic, uses a five-digit data link sequence number confirmed between air traffic control and the pilots of the aircraft before the aircraft proceeds to cross the ocean.
[src:defense-c4isr/data-link] This system uses the aircraft's flight management computer to send location, speed and altitude information about the aircraft to the ATC.
[src:defense-c4isr/data-link] ATC can then send messages to the aircraft regarding any necessary change of course.
[src:defense-c4isr/data-link] In unmanned aircraft, land vehicles, boats, and spacecraft, a two-way (full-duplex or half-duplex) data-link is used to send control signals, and to receive telemetry.
[src:defense-c4isr/intelligence-surveillance-target-acquisition-and-reconnaissance] ISR is the coordinated and integrated acquisition, processing and provision of timely, accurate, relevant, coherent and assured information and intelligence to support commanders' conduct of activities.
[src:defense-c4isr/intelligence-surveillance-target-acquisition-and-reconnaissance] Land, sea, air and space platforms have critical ISR roles in supporting operations in general.
[src:defense-c4isr/intelligence-surveillance-target-acquisition-and-reconnaissance] By massing ISR assets, an improved clarity and depth of knowledge can be established.
[src:defense-c4isr/intelligence-surveillance-target-acquisition-and-reconnaissance] ISR encompasses multiple activities related to the planning and operation of systems that collect, process, and disseminate data in support of current and future military operations.
[src:defense-c4isr/intelligence-surveillance-target-acquisition-and-reconnaissance] In July 2021 the NDAA budget markup by the House Armed Services Committee sought to retain ISR resources such as the RQ-4 Global Hawk, the E-8 Joint Surveillance Radar and Attack System (JSTARS) which the Air Force is seeking to divest.
[src:defense-c4isr/intelligence-surveillance-target-acquisition-and-reconnaissance] The intelligence data provided by these ISR systems can take many forms, including optical, radar, or infrared images or electronic signals.
[src:defense-c4isr/intelligence-surveillance-target-acquisition-and-reconnaissance] Effective ISR data can provide early warning of enemy threats as well as enable military forces to increase effectiveness, coordination, and lethality, and demand for ISR capabilities to support ongoing military operations has increased.
[src:defense-c4isr/intelligence-surveillance-target-acquisition-and-reconnaissance] In December 2021, the US Navy began testing the usefulness and effectiveness of uncrewed "saildrones" at recognizing targets of interest on the high seas.
[src:defense-c4isr/intelligence-surveillance-target-acquisition-and-reconnaissance] Most space-based intelligence collection capabilities consist of multiple satellites operating in concert, or supplemented by other sensors, when continuous surveillance of an area is desired.
[src:defense-c4isr/intelligence-surveillance-target-acquisition-and-reconnaissance] The United States Space Force, National Reconnaissance Office (NRO), and National Geospatial-Intelligence Agency (NGA) share the satellite-based ISR task as of 2021.
[src:defense-c4isr/intelligence-surveillance-target-acquisition-and-reconnaissance] From 2018, the NGA has used Data transformation services (DTS), to convert raw sensor data into a format usable by its mission partners, who are government agencies whose names are classified.
[src:defense-c4isr/intelligence-surveillance-target-acquisition-and-reconnaissance] In light of the 2022 Russian invasion of Ukraine, the NGA has taken operational control of DoD's Project Maven, the AI ISR project for area defense, to identify point targets for ISR.
[src:defense-c4isr/intelligence-surveillance-target-acquisition-and-reconnaissance] The NGA uses OREN, the Odyssey GEOINT Edge Node for National System for Geospatial Intelligence, or NGS.
[src:defense-c4isr/intelligence-surveillance-target-acquisition-and-reconnaissance] The Joint Regional Edge Node (JREN) is on-deck for distributing nearly a petabyte to the Combatant Commands in the next year, for 2023, an increase by a factor of 10.
[src:defense-c4isr/intelligence-surveillance-target-acquisition-and-reconnaissance] NRO "has a proven track record in [ISR]", insists one of the founders of the US Space Force, who defends the capability of the NRO over the ambition of the Space Force to take over the role of ISR.
[src:defense-c4isr/intelligence-surveillance-target-acquisition-and-reconnaissance] GMTI (ground moving target indicator) data is an objective for Space Force, NGA, and NRO.
[src:defense-c4isr/intelligence-surveillance-target-acquisition-and-reconnaissance] Ukraine's soldiers are using FPV drones on the battlefield, armed with munitions.
[src:defense-c4isr/intelligence-surveillance-target-acquisition-and-reconnaissance] ISR concepts are also associated with certain intelligence units, for instance Task Force ODIN, ISR TF (Company+) in Bosnia, Kosovo and Afghanistan.
[src:defense-c4isr/intelligence-surveillance-target-acquisition-and-reconnaissance] ISTAR is the process of integrating the intelligence process with surveillance, target acquisition and reconnaissance tasks in order to improve a commander's situational awareness and consequently their decision making.
[src:defense-c4isr/intelligence-surveillance-target-acquisition-and-reconnaissance] The inclusion of the "I" is important as it recognizes the importance of taking the information from all the sensors and processing it into useful knowledge.
[src:defense-c4isr/intelligence-surveillance-target-acquisition-and-reconnaissance] There are several variations on the "ISTAR" acronym.
[src:defense-c4isr/intelligence-surveillance-target-acquisition-and-reconnaissance] Some variations reflect specific emphasis on certain aspects of ISTAR.
[src:defense-c4isr/intelligence-surveillance-target-acquisition-and-reconnaissance] A term used when emphasis is to be placed on the sensing component of ISTAR.
[src:defense-c4isr/intelligence-surveillance-target-acquisition-and-reconnaissance] RSTA is used by the US Army in place of STAR or ISTAR.
[src:defense-c4isr/intelligence-surveillance-target-acquisition-and-reconnaissance] Also, a term used to identify certain US Army units: for instance, 3rd Squadron, 153rd RSTA.
[src:defense-c4isr/intelligence-surveillance-target-acquisition-and-reconnaissance] These units serve a similar role to the below mentioned US Marine Corps STA platoons, but on a larger scale.
[src:defense-c4isr/link-16] Link 16 enables military aircraft, ships, and ground forces to exchange their tactical picture in near-real time; it also supports the exchange of text messages, imagery, and voice (the latter on two digital channels: 2.4 kbit/s or 16 kbit/s in any combination).
[src:defense-c4isr/link-16] It is one of the digital services of the JTIDS / MIDS in NATO's *Standardization Agreement* STANAG 5516.
[src:defense-c4isr/link-16] MIL-STD-6016 is the related United States Department of Defense Link 16 MIL-STD.
[src:defense-c4isr/link-16] This frequency range limits the exchange of information to users within line-of-sight of one another, although with satellite capabilities and ad hoc protocols, it is nowadays possible to pass Link 16 data over long-haul protocols such as TCP/IP using MIL-STD 3011 (JREAP) or STANAG 5602 (SIMPLE).
[src:defense-c4isr/link-16] It uses the transmission characteristics and protocols, conventions, and fixed-length or variable length message formats defined by MIL-STD 6016 and STANAG 5516 (formerly the JTIDS technical interface design plan).
[src:defense-c4isr/link-16] Information is typically passed at one of three data rates: 31.6, 57.6, or 115.2 kilobits per second (kbit/s), although the radios and frequency-hopping spread spectrum (FHSS) waveform itself can support throughput values well over 1 Mbit/s.
[src:defense-c4isr/link-16] Link 16 information is primarily coded in J-series messages which are binary data words with well-defined meanings.
[src:defense-c4isr/link-16] Link 16 is intended to advance Tactical Data Links (TDLs) as the NATO standard for data link information exchange.
[src:defense-c4isr/link-16] Link 16 equipment is located in ground, airborne, and sea-based air defense platforms and selected fighter aircraft.
[src:defense-c4isr/link-16] The U.S. industry is now developing a new Link 16 SCA compliant radio MIDS-JTRS which currently is projected to implement nine various tactical waveforms, including Link 16.
[src:defense-c4isr/link-16] The MIDS program, which manage the development of the American aspect of communication component for Link 16, is managed by the International Program Office located in San Diego, California.
[src:defense-c4isr/link-16] In the United States, the lead Air Force command for the MIL-STD-6016 standard, plans, and requirements is the Air Force Global Cyberspace Integration Center at Langley AFB, with JTIDS program execution managed by the 653d Electronic Systems Wing at Hanscom Air Force Base near Boston, Massachusetts.
[src:defense-c4isr/link-16] The MIL-STD-6016 Standard configuration management custodian is the Defense Information Systems Agency.
[src:defense-c4isr/link-16] Army is integrating Link 16 into select command and control elements of its UH-60 Black Hawk fleet, and intends to pursue fielding to AH-64 Apache and other aviation assets.
[src:defense-c4isr/link-16] The USAF will add Link 16 to its Rockwell B-1 Lancer and Boeing B-52 Stratofortress bombers with the Common Link Integration Processing system.
[src:defense-c4isr/link-16] Early versions of the Lockheed Martin F-22 Raptor could only receive but not transmit Link 16 data, on the basis that transmitting data would reveal its location.
[src:defense-c4isr/link-16] Upgrades to the F-22 have since given it the ability to transmit Link 16 as well.
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] Inadequate situation awareness has been identified as one of the primary causal factors in accidents attributed to human error.
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] People with the highest levels of situational awareness not only perceive the relevant information for their goals and decisions, but are also able to integrate that information to understand its meaning or significance, and are able to project likely or possible future scenarios.
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] These higher levels of situational awareness are critical for proactive decision making in demanding environments.
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] Three aspects of situational awareness have been the focus in research: situational awareness states, situational awareness systems, and situational awareness processes.
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] *Situational awareness states*refers to the actual level of awareness people have of the situation.
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] *Situational awareness systems* refers to technologies that are developed to support situational awareness in many environments.
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] *Situational awareness processes* refers to the updating of situational awareness states, and what guides the moment-to-moment change of situational awareness.
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] Although the term itself is fairly recent, the concept has roots in the history of military theory—it is recognizable in Sun Tzu's *The Art of War*, for example.
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] The term can be traced to World War I, where it was recognized as a crucial skill for crews in military aircraft.
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] There is evidence that the term *situational awareness* was first employed at the Douglas Aircraft Company during human factors engineering research while developing vertical and horizontal situation displays and evaluating digital-control placement for the next generation of commercial aircraft.
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] Research programs in flight-crew computer interaction and mental workload measurement built on the concept of awareness measurement from a series of experiments that measured contingency awareness during learning, and later extended to mental workload and fatigue.
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] Situation awareness appears in the technical literature as early as 1983, when describing the benefits of a prototype touch-screen navigation display.
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] During the early 1980s, integrated "vertical-situation" and "horizontal-situation" displays were being developed for commercial aircraft to replace multiple electro-mechanical instruments.
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] Integrated situation displays combined the information from several instruments enabling more efficient access to critical flight parameters, thereby improving situational awareness and reducing pilot workload.
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] The term was first defined formally by Endsley in 1988.
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] Before being widely adopted by human factors scientists in the 1990s, the term is said to have been used by United States Air Force (USAF) fighter aircrew returning from war in Korea and Vietnam.
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] They identified having good situation awareness as the decisive factor in air combat engagements—the "ace factor".
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] Survival in a dogfight was typically a matter of observing the opponent's current move and anticipating his next move a fraction of a second before he could observe and anticipate it himself.
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] USAF pilots also came to equate situational awareness with the "observe" and "orient" phases of the famous observe-orient-decide-act loop (OODA loop), or Boyd cycle, as described by the USAF war theorist Col.
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] In combat, the winning strategy is to "get inside" your opponent's OODA loop, not just by making one's own decisions quicker, but also by having better situation awareness than one's opponent, and even changing the situation in ways that the opponent cannot monitor or even comprehend.
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] Losing one's own situation awareness, in contrast, equates to being "out of the loop".
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] Clearly, situational awareness has far-reaching applications, as it is necessary for individuals and teams to function effectively in their environment.
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] Thus, situational awareness has gone far beyond the field of aviation to work being conducted in a wide variety of environments.
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] Situation awareness is being studied in such diverse areas as air traffic control, nuclear power plant operation, emergency response, maritime operations, space, oil and gas drilling, vehicle operation, and health care (e.g. anesthesiology and nursing).
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] The most widely cited and accepted model of SA was developed by Dr.
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] Mica Endsley, which has been shown to be largely supported by research findings.
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] Lee, Cassano-Pinche, and Vicente found that Endsley's Model of SA received 50% more citations following its publication than any other paper in Human Factors compared to other papers in the 30-year period of their review.
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] Endsley's model describes the cognitive processes and mechanisms that are used by people to assess situations to develop SA, and the task and environmental factors that also affect their ability to get SA.
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] It describes in detail the three levels of SA formation: perception, comprehension, and projection.
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] Endsley's model shows how SA "provides the primary basis for subsequent decision making and performance in the operation of complex, dynamic systems".
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] Although alone it cannot guarantee successful decision making, SA does support the necessary input processes (e.g., cue recognition, situation assessment, prediction) upon which good decisions are based.
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] SA also involves both a temporal and a spatial component.
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] Time is an important concept in SA, as SA is a dynamic construct, changing at a tempo dictated by the actions of individuals, task characteristics, and the surrounding environment.
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] As new inputs enter the system, the individual incorporates them into this mental representation, making changes as necessary in plans and actions in order to achieve the desired goals.
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] SA also involves spatial knowledge about the activities and events occurring in a specific location of interest to the individual.
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] Thus, the concept of SA includes perception, comprehension, and projection of situational information, as well as temporal and spatial components.
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] Endsley's model of SA illustrates several variables that can influence the development and maintenance of SA, including individual, task, and environmental factors.
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] Experience and training have a significant impact on people's ability to develop SA, due to its impact on the development of mental models that reduce processing demands and help people to better prioritize their goals.
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] In addition, it has been found that individuals vary in their ability to acquire SA; thus, simply providing the same system and training will not ensure similar SA across different individuals.
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] Research has shown that there are a number of factors that make some people better at SA than others including differences in spatial abilities and multi-tasking skills.
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] Criticisms of the SA construct and the model are generally viewed as unfounded and addressed.
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] The Endsley model is very detailed in describing the exact cognitive processes involved in SA.
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] Nevertheless, there are several criticisms of SA.
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] One criticism is the danger of circularity with SA: "How does one know that SA was lost?
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] Because the human responded inappropriately.
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] Why did the human respond inappropriately?
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] Because SA was lost." Building on the circularity concern, others deemed SA a folk model on the basis that it is frequently overgeneralized and immune to falsification.
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] A recent review and meta-analysis of SA measures showed they were highly correlated or predictive of performance, which initially appears to provide strong quantitative evidence refuting criticisms of SA.
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] However, the inclusion criteria in this meta-analysis was limited to positive correlations reaching desirable levels of statistical significance.
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] That is, more desirable results hypothesis supporting results were included while the less desirable results, contradicting the hypothesis, were excluded.
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] The justification was "Not all measures of SA are relevant to performance." This an example of a circular analysis or double-dipping, where the dataset being analyzed are selected based on the outcome from analyzing the same dataset.
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] Because only more desirable effects were included, the results of this meta-analysis were predetermined – predictive measures of SA were predictive.
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] Further, there were inflated estimates of mean effect sizes compared to an analysis that did not select results using statistical significance.
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] Determining the relevance of SA based on the desirability of outcomes and analyzing only supporting results is a circular conceptualization of SA and revives concerns about the falsifiability of SA.
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] Several cognitive processes related to situation awareness are briefly described in this section.
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] The matrix shown below attempts to illustrate the relationship among some of these concepts.
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] Note that *situation awareness* and *situational assessment* are more commonly discussed in information fusion complex domains such as aviation and military operations and relate more to achieving immediate tactical objectives.
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] *Sensemaking* and achieving *understanding* are more commonly found in industry and the organizational psychology literature and often relate to achieving long-term strategic objectives.
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] There are also biological mediators of situational awareness, most notably hormones such as testosterone, and neurotransmitters such as dopamine and norepinephrine.
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] Situational understanding is the same as Level 2 SA in the Endsley model—the comprehension of the meaning of the information as integrated with each other and in terms of the individual's goals.
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] It is the "so what" of the data that is perceived.
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] In brief, *situation awareness* is viewed as "a state of knowledge," and *situational assessment* as "the processes" used to achieve that knowledge.
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] Endsley argues that "it is important to distinguish the term situation awareness, as a state of knowledge, from the processes used to achieve that state.
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] For example, one's current awareness can determine what one pays attention to next and how one interprets the information perceived.
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] Accurate mental models are one of the prerequisites for achieving SA.
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] A mental model can be described as a set of well-defined, highly organized yet dynamic knowledge structures developed over time from experience.
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] The volume of available data inherent in complex operational environments can overwhelm the capability of novice decision makers to attend, process, and integrate this information efficiently, resulting in information overload and negatively impacting their SA.
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] In contrast, experienced decision makers assess and interpret the current situation (Level 1 and 2 SA) and select an appropriate action based on conceptual patterns stored in their long-term memory as "mental models".
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] Cues in the environment activate these mental models, which in turn guide their decision-making process.
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] In brief, sensemaking is viewed more as "a motivated, continuous effort to understand connections (which can be among people, places, and events) in order to anticipate their trajectories and act effectively", rather than the state of knowledge underlying situation awareness.
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] Endsley points out that as an effortful process, sensemaking is actually considering a subset of the processes used to maintain situation awareness.
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] In many systems and organizations, people work not just as individuals, but as members of a team.
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] Thus, it is necessary to consider the SA of not just individual team members, but also the SA of the team as a whole.
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] To begin to understand what is needed for SA within teams, it is first necessary to clearly define what constitutes a team.
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] A team is not just any group of individuals; rather teams have a few defining characteristics.
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] Team SA is defined as "the degree to which every team member possesses the SA required for his or her responsibilities".
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] The success or failure of a team depends on the success or failure of each of its team members.
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] If any one of the team members has poor SA, it can lead to a critical error in performance that can undermine the success of the entire team.
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] By this definition, each team member needs to have a high level of SA on those factors that are relevant for his or her job.
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] It is not sufficient for one member of the team to be aware of critical information if the team member who needs that information is not aware.
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] Therefore, team members need to be successful in communicating information between them (including how they are interpreting or projecting changes in the situation to form level 2 and 3 SA) or in each independently being able to get the information they need.
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] In a team, each member has a subgoal pertinent to his/her specific role that feeds into the overall team goal.
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] Associated with each member's subgoal are a set of SA elements about which he/she is concerned.
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] As the members of a team are essentially interdependent in meeting the overall team goal, some overlap between each member's subgoal and their SA requirements will be present.
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] It is this subset of information that constitutes much of team coordination.
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] That coordination may occur as a verbal exchange, a duplication of displayed information, or by some other means.
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] Shared situation awareness can be defined as "the degree to which team members possess the same SA on shared SA requirements".
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] As implied by this definition, there are information requirements that are relevant to multiple team members.
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] A major part of teamwork involves the area where these SA requirements overlap—the shared SA requirements that exist as a function of the essential interdependency of the team members.
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] In a poorly functioning team, two or more members may have different assessments on these shared SA requirements and thus behave in an uncoordinated or even counter-productive fashion.
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] Yet in a smoothly functioning team, each team member shares a common understanding of what is happening on those SA elements that are common—*shared SA*.
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] Thus, shared SA refers to the degree to which people have a common understanding of information that is in the overlap of the SA requirements of the team members.
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] Clearly, each team member is aware of much that is not pertinent to the others on the team.
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] Sharing every detail of each person's job would create information overload to sort through to get needed information.
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] It is only that information which is relevant to the SA requirements of each team member that needs to be shared.
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] Endsley and Jones describe a model of team situation awareness as a means of conceptualizing how teams develop high levels of shared SA across members.
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] Each of these four factors—requirements, devices, mechanisms and processes—act to help build team and shared SA.
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] **Team SA devices** – the devices available for sharing this information, which can include direct communication (both verbal and non-verbal), shared displays (e.g., visual or audio displays, or tactile devices), or a shared environment.
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] As non-verbal communication, such as gestures and display of local artifacts, and a shared environment are usually not available in distributed teams, this places far more emphasis on verbal communication and communication technologies for creating shared information displays.
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] **Team SA mechanisms** – the degree to which team members possess mechanisms, such as shared mental models, which support their ability to interpret information in the same way and make accurate projections regarding each other's actions.
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] The possession of shared mental models can greatly facilitate communication and coordination in team settings.
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] While the SA construct has been widely researched, the multivariate nature of SA poses a considerable challenge to its quantification and measurement.
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] In general, techniques vary in terms of direct measurement of SA (e.g., objective real-time probes or subjective questionnaires assessing perceived SA) or methods that infer SA based on operator behavior or performance.
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] Direct measures are typically considered to be "product-oriented" in that these techniques assess an SA outcome; inferred measures are considered to be "process-oriented," focusing on the underlying processes or mechanisms required to achieve SA.
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] These SA measurement approaches are further described next.
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] Objective measures directly assess SA by comparing an individual's perceptions of the situation or environment to some "ground truth" reality.
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] Specifically, objective measures collect data from the individual on his or her perceptions of the situation and compare them to what is actually happening to score the accuracy of their SA at a given moment in time.
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] Thus, this type of assessment provides a direct measure of SA and does not require operators or observers to make judgments about situational knowledge on the basis of incomplete information.
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] Subjective measures directly assess SA by asking individuals to rate their own or the observed SA of individuals on an anchored scale (e.g., participant situation awareness questionnaire; the situation awareness rating technique).
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] Subjective measures of SA are attractive in that they are relatively straightforward and easy to administer.
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] However, several limitations should be noted.
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] Individuals making subjective assessments of their own SA are often unaware of information they do not know (the unknown unknowns).
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] Subjective measures also tend to be global in nature, and, as such, do not fully exploit the multivariate nature of SA to provide the detailed diagnostics available with objective measures.
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] Nevertheless, self-ratings may be useful in that they can provide an assessment of operators' degree of confidence in their SA and their own performance.
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] Subjective estimates of an individual's SA may also be made by experienced observers (e.g., peers, commanders, or trained external experts).
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] However, observers have only limited knowledge about the operator's concept of the situation and cannot have complete insight into the mental state of the individual being evaluated.
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] Thus, observers are forced to rely more on operators' observable actions and verbalizations to infer their level of SA.
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] In this case, such actions and verbalizations are best assessed using performance and behavioral measures of SA, as described next.
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] Performance measures infer SA from the end result (i.e., task performance outcomes), based on the assumption that better performance indicates better SA.
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] Common performance metrics include quantity of output or productivity level, time to perform the task or respond to an event, and the accuracy of the response or, conversely, the number of errors committed.
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] The main advantage of performance measures is that these can be collected objectively and without disrupting task performance.
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] However, although evidence exists to suggest a positive relation between SA and performance, this connection is probabilistic and not always direct and unequivocal.
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] In other words, good SA does not always lead to good performance and poor SA does not always lead to poor performance.
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] Thus, performance measures should be used in conjunction with other measures of SA that directly assess this construct.
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] Behavioral measures also infer SA from the actions that individuals choose to take, based on the assumption that good actions will follow from good SA and vice versa.
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] Behavioral measures rely primarily on observer ratings, and are, thus, somewhat subjective in nature.
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] To address this limitation, observers can be asked to evaluate the degree to which individuals are carrying out actions and exhibiting behaviors that would be expected to promote the achievement of higher levels of SA.
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] This approach removes some of the subjectivity associated with making judgments about an individual's internal state of knowledge by allowing them to make judgments about SA indicators that are more readily observable.
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] Process indices examine how individuals process information in their environment, such as by analyzing communication patterns between team members or using eye tracking devices.
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] Team communication (particularly verbal communication) supports the knowledge building and information processing that leads to SA construction.
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] Psycho-physiological measures also serve as process indices of operator SA by providing an assessment of the relationship between human performance and a corrected change in the operator's physiology.
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] In other words, cognitive activity is associated with changes in the operator's physiological states.
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] For example, the operator's overall functional state (as assessed using psycho-physiological measures, such as electroencephalography data, eyeblinks, and cardiac activity) may indicate as to whether the operator is sleep fatigued at one end of the continuum, or mentally overloaded at the other end.
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] In addition, it is also possible to use psycho-physiological measures to monitor operators' environmental expectancies, that is, their physiological responses to upcoming events, as a measure of their current level of SA.
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] The multivariate nature of SA significantly complicates its quantification and measurement, as it is conceivable that a metric may only tap into one aspect of the operator's SA.
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] Further, studies have shown that different types of SA measures do not always correlate strongly with each other.
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] Accordingly, rather than rely on a single approach or metric, valid and reliable measurement of SA should utilize a battery of distinct yet related measures that complement each other.
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] Such a multifaceted approach to SA measurement capitalizes on the strengths of each measure while minimizing the limitations inherent in each.
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] Situation awareness is limited by sensory input and available attention, by the individual's knowledge and experience, and by their ability to analyse the available information effectively.
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] Attention is a limited resource, and may be reduced by distraction and task loading.
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] Comprehension of the situation and projection of future status depend heavily on relevant knowledge, understanding, and experience in similar environments.
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] Team SA is less limited by these factors, as there is a wider knowledge and experience base, but it is limited by the effectiveness of communication within the team.
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] Following Endsley's paradigm and with cognitive resource management model with neurofeedback techniques, Spanish Pedagogist María Gabriela López García (2010) implemented and developed a new SA training pattern.
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] The first organization to implement this new pattern design by López García is the SPAF (Spanish Air Force).
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] She has trained EF-18 fighter pilots and Canadair firefighters.
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] This situation awareness training aims to avoid losing SA and provide pilots with cognitive resources to always operate below the maximum workload that they can withstand.
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] This provides not only a lower probability of incidents and accidents by human factors, but the hours of operation are at their optimum efficiency, extending the operating life of systems and operators.
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] Situation awareness for first responders in medical situations also includes evaluating and understanding what happened to avoid injury of responders and also to provide information to other rescue agencies which may need to know what the situation is via radio before their arrival on the scene.
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] In a medical context, situation awareness is applied to avoid further injury to already-injured individuals, to avoid injury to medical responders, and to inform other potential responders of hazardous conditions before their arrival.
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] A loss in situational awareness has led to many transportation accidents, including the 1991 Los Angeles Airport runway collision and the 2015 Philadelphia train derailment.
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] Within the search and rescue context, situational awareness is applied primarily to avoid injury to search crews by being aware of the environment, the lay of the land, and the many other factors of influence within one's surroundings which assists in the location of injured or missing individuals.
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] Public safety agencies are increasingly using situational awareness applications like Android Tactical Assault Kit on mobile devices and even robots to improve situational awareness.
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] In the United States Forest Service the use of chainsaws and crosscut saws requires training and certification.
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] A great deal of that training describes situational awareness as an approach toward environmental awareness but also self-awareness which includes being aware of one's own emotional attitude, tiredness, and even caloric intake.
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] Situational awareness in the forest context also includes evaluating the environment and the potential safety hazards within a saw crew's area of influence.
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] As a sawyer approaches a task, the ground, wind, cloud cover, hillsides, and many other factors are examined and are considered proactively as part of trained sawyers' ingrained training.
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] Dead or diseased trees within the reach of saw team crews are evaluated, and the strength and direction of the wind is evaluated.
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] In cybersecurity, situational awareness for threat operations is being able to perceive threat activity and vulnerability in context so that the following can be actively defended: data, information, knowledge, and wisdom from compromise.
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] Situational awareness is achieved by developing and using solutions that often consume data and information from many different sources.
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] Technology and algorithms are then used to apply knowledge and wisdom in order to discern patterns of behavior that point to possible, probable, and real threats.
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] Different studies have analyzed the perception of security and privacy in the context of eHealth, network security, or using collaborative approaches to improve the awareness of users.
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] There are also research efforts to automate the processing of communication network information to obtain or improve cyber-situational awareness.
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] As the capabilities of technological agents increase, it becomes more important that their actions and underlying rational becomes transparent.
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] In the military realm, agent transparency has been investigated as unmanned vehicles are being employed more frequently.
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] Army Research Laboratory reported the Situation Awareness-based Agent Transparency (SAT), a model designed to increase transparency through user interface design.
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] The greater the level of situational awareness, they claimed, the more information the agent conveys to the user.
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] Army Research Laboratory evaluated how varying transparency levels in the SAT affects the operator workload and a human's understanding of when it is necessary to intervene in the agent's decision-making.
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] The researchers refer to this supervisory judgement as calibration.
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] The group split their SAT model research into two efforts: the Intelligent Agent Transparency in Human Agent Transparency for Multi UxV Management (IMPACT) and the Autonomous Squad Member (ASM) projects.
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] Scientists provided three standard levels of SAT in addition to a fourth level which included the agent's level of uncertainty in its decision in unmanned vehicles.
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] The stated goal of this research was to determine how modifying levels of SAT affected user performance, situation awareness, and confidence in the agent.
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] The scientists stated that their experimental results support that increased agent transparency improved the performance of the operator and human confidence in the agent without a significant effect on the workload.
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] When the agent communicated levels of uncertainty in the task assigned, those involved in the experimentation displayed more trust in the agent.
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] The ASM research was conducted by providing a simulation game in which the participant had to complete a training course with an ASM, a ground robot that communicates with infantry.
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] The participants had to multitask, evaluating potential threats while monitoring the ASM's communications on the interface.
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] According to that research, experimental results demonstrated that the greatest confidence calibration occurred when the agent communicated information of all three levels of SAT.
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] Army Research Laboratory developed transparency visualization concepts in which the agents can communicate their plans, motivations, and projected outcomes through icons.
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] The agent has been reported to be able to relate its resource usage, reasoning, predicted resource loss, progress towards task completion, etc.
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] Unlike in the IMPACT research, the agent informing the user of its level of uncertainty in decision making, no increase in trust was observed.
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] Crowdsourcing, made possible by the rise of social media and ubiquitous mobile access has a potential for considerably enhancing situation awareness of both responsible authorities and citizens themselves for emergency and crisis situations by employing or using "citizens as sensors".
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] For instance, analysis of content posted on online social media like Facebook and Twitter using data mining, machine learning and natural language processing techniques may provide situational information.
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] A crowdsourcing approach to sensing, particularly in crisis situations, has been referred to as *crowdsensing*.
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] A Cloud-based Geographic Information System (GIS) with a display of structured data refers to a system that utilizes cloud computing technology to store, manage, analyze, and visualize geographic data in a structured format.
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] This approach offers several advantages, including accessibility, scalability, and collaboration, compared to traditional on-premises GIS systems.
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] There are two training scenarios designed to increase the situational awareness skills of military professionals and first responders in police and emergency services.
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] The first, Kim's Game, has a more common place in the Marine Corps sniper school and police academies.
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] The name is derived from the novel Kim which references the game to a spy school lesson.
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] The game involves a tray with various items such as spoons, pencils, bullets, and any other items the soldiers would be familiar with.
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] The participants are given one minute to view all of these items before they are covered up with a blanket.
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] The participants would then individually list the items that they saw; the one with the most correct answers would win the game.
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] The same game is played in young scouting and Girl Guide groups as well to teach children quick memorisation skills.
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] The second method is a more practical military application of Kim's Game.
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] It starts with a field area (jungle, bush or forest) of about five meters wide to 10 meters deep where various items, some camouflaged and some not, are to be located in the area on the ground and in the trees at eye level.
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] Again, these items would be ones that are familiar to the soldiers undergoing the exercise.
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] The participants would be given 10 minutes to view the area from one place and take a mental note of the items they saw.
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] Once their 10 minutes are up, the soldier would then be required to do a repetition of certain exercises such as burpees, designed to simulate the stress of a physically demanding environment.
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] Once the participant completes the exercise, they would list the items they saw.
[src:defense-c4isr/situation-awareness] The points would be tallied in the end to find the winner.
